#compdef v3c
# =============================================================================
# v3c — the Virgil III compiler (codename "Aeneas"), Ben L. Titzer's fast and
#       lightweight systems programming language compiler.  Produces optimized
#       standalone native executables for x86 / x86-64 (linux, darwin),
#       WebAssembly (with and without WasmGC), JVM JAR files, or runs
#       programs directly on a built-in interpreter for quick turnaround.
#       Virgil is currently being used as the implementation language for
#       Wizard — a next-generation WebAssembly virtual machine — at Carnegie
#       Mellon University.  Designed for the LOWEST level of software
#       systems: features that let programs talk directly to kernels,
#       generate machine code at runtime, implement their own garbage
#       collection.  Blends functional and object-oriented paradigms in a
#       statically-typed language with classes, functions, tuples, type
#       parameters, and algebraic data types.
#
# Author:  Ben L. Titzer (titzer) — formerly Google V8 team, now CMU; author
#          of the WebAssembly specification and reference interpreter
# Source:  https://github.com/titzer/virgil
# CLI:     aeneas/src/main/CLOptions.v3 (uses Virgil stdlib lib/util/Option.v3)
# Library: Virgil stdlib "Option.v3" — BasicOptions + OptionGroup
#          ("Type-parameterized Option<T> classes with hash-map-dispatch
#           Options collection and per-category OptionGroup help printing")
# License: Apache 2.0
# Status:  Stable — 1403+ stars; Virgil bootstraps itself (the v3c compiler
#          is written entirely in Virgil); active development since 2009.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 58TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 58TH LANGUAGE (Virgil III, via v3c / aeneas) and 240TH CLI library
# variant.  Virgil joins the small set of self-hosting languages whose
# compiler binary uses a CLI library WRITTEN IN THE LANGUAGE ITSELF
# (alongside Rust's clap-derive, Crystal's Admiral, Pony's cli stdlib,
# Beef's parsing, Zig's std.process.argsAlloc, Jakt R??, Beluga R??).
# New language tally: 58 — F#=2, Beluga=2, Jakt=1, Ur/Web=1, REBOL=1,
# Io=1, Pure=1, Yeti=1, Whiley=1, Boogie=1, Beef=1, Luau=1, Tact=1,
# min=1, Daml=1, Mun=1, Virgil=1.  Top-language tally remains Rust=32 /
# Go=32 / TS-Node=32 (THREE-WAY TIE).
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS VIRGIL'S CLI LIBRARY AND WHY IS IT THE 58TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE?
#
# Virgil's stdlib `lib/util/Option.v3` (Apache-2.0, Copyright 2010 Google
# — Ben Titzer wrote the initial version while at Google before founding
# the WebAssembly project) is **Virgil's built-in command-line option
# parsing framework**.  It is THE library every Virgil binary uses — the
# v3c compiler itself, the v3i interpreter, the v3db debugger, and every
# application in `apps/` (Btime, vctags, EchoServerClient, etc.).  Virgil
# has no third-party CLI ecosystem; the stdlib library IS the CLI surface
# every Virgil program builds against.
#
# Virgil's CLI library is DISTINCT from every documented CLI library on
# SIX specific axes:
#
#   1. TYPE-PARAMETERIZED Option<T> GENERIC CLASS — the core abstraction
#      is `Option<T>` parameterized by the option's value type, with a
#      `parseFun: string -> T` field that converts the raw string to T:
#         class Option<T> extends Opt {
#             def init: T;
#             def parseFun: string -> T;
#             var onSetFun: T -> void;
#             var val: T;
#             new(name: string, init, parseFun)
#                 : super(name) { val = init; }
#             def parse(val: string) {
#                 this.val = parseFun(val);
#                 if (onSetFun != null) onSetFun(this.val);
#             }
#             def onSet(f: T -> void) -> this { this.onSetFun = f; }
#             def get() -> T { return val; }
#         }
#      The base class `Opt(name: string)` hides the type variable so
#      `Option<int>`, `Option<bool>`, `Option<string>` can all live in
#      the same `Strings.newMap<Opt>()` hash table.  This is **first-
#      class type-parameterized options + variance erasure for collection
#      storage** — a Java-generics-style design implemented in Virgil's
#      class system.
#      Compare:
#        clap (Rust):     proc-macro derive over struct fields
#        argparse (Py):   add_argument(type=int) — runtime type tag
#        getopt_long (C): switch-on-flag-char manual decoding
#        BasicOptions:    `Option<T>` typed by Virgil's class system,
#                         erased to `Opt` for storage.
#      Virgil's `Option<T>` is **closer to Swift's `KeyPath<Root,Value>`
#      pattern** than to any documented argparse design — typed handle
#      at construction, erased for storage, recovered at use.
#
#   2. CHAINABLE `.onSet(callback)` HOOK FOR DEPENDENT OPTIONS — the
#      `onSet` method returns `this`, enabling fluent chaining:
#         def FUN_EXPRS = langOpt.newBoolOption("fun-exprs", true,
#             "Enable function expressions.").onSet(implySimpleBodies);
#      When the option's `parse()` runs, it fires the callback with the
#      new value.  This is used in v3c to implement "setting option A
#      implies setting option B" semantics — e.g. `-fun-exprs` implies
#      `-simple-bodies`.  Compare:
#        argparse (Py):    no onSet — caller polls args.flag after parse
#        clap (Rust):      no onSet — derive macro emits a struct, you
#                          implement dependent logic by inspecting it
#        cmdliner (OCaml): combine via `Term.app`, not callback hook
#        cobra (Go):       `PreRun` runs once per command, not per option
#        BasicOptions:     PER-OPTION ON-SET callback, fired during
#                          parse (UNIQUE among documented argparse
#                          libraries — option-level effect during parsing)
#      The on-set callback closes over arbitrary state; in v3c it sets
#      sibling options atomically as side-effects of parsing.
#
#   3. OptionGroup CATEGORIZATION WITH PER-GROUP HELP PRINTING — Virgil
#      separates the parser's collection (`BasicOptions`) from the
#      help-output groupings:
#         class OptionGroup(name: string, o: BasicOptions) {
#             var list: List<(Opt, string, string)>;
#             def newIntOption(name, defval, help)    => ...
#             def newBoolOption(name, defval, help)   => ...
#             def newStringOption(name, defval, help) => ...
#             def newPathOption(name, defval, help)   => ...
#             def newSizeOption(name, defval, help)   => ...
#             def newAddrOption(name, defval, help)   => ...
#             def newMatcherOption(name, help)        => ...
#             def newEmptyOption(name, help)          => ...
#             def print(buf: TerminalBuffer);  // per-group help printer
#         }
#      Each `OptionGroup` holds a sub-list of options registered under
#      its category, but also registers them into the shared parser.
#      In v3c, there are **11 OptionGroup instances**:
#         actionOpt   = OptionGroup.new("ACTION", options)
#         sharedOpt   = OptionGroup.new("SHARED", options)
#         runOpt      = OptionGroup.new("RUN", options)
#         testOpt     = OptionGroup.new("TEST", options)
#         compileOpt  = OptionGroup.new("COMPILE", options)
#         wasmOpt     = OptionGroup.new("WASM TARGET", options)
#         wasmgcOpt   = OptionGroup.new("WASM GC TARGET", options)
#         jvmOpt      = OptionGroup.new("JVM TARGET", options)
#         debugOpt    = OptionGroup.new("DEBUGGING", options)
#         langOpt     = OptionGroup.new("LANGUAGE", options)
#         rtOpt       = OptionGroup.new("RUNTIME", options)
#      Each group calls `.print(buf)` for its own section of help text.
#      Compare:
#        clap (Rust):     `#[command(next_help_heading="...")]` per arg
#        argparse (Py):   `add_argument_group(...)` — similar two-level
#        cmdliner (OCaml):`Manpage.Block` markup — manual help layout
#        BasicOptions:    OptionGroup is the categorization AND a
#                         help-printing dispatcher — a separate class
#                         from the parser collection.
#      First documented CLI library to use the "two-tier registration"
#      pattern (parser plus per-group display registry) — most other
#      libraries fold help-grouping metadata into the option struct
#      itself rather than into a separate group object.
#
#   4. CONFIGURABLE `numHyphens` (SINGLE OR DOUBLE) — Virgil's parser
#      accepts a SINGLE-HYPHEN convention by default (`-help`, `-run`,
#      `-target=wasm`) but supports a `numHyphens = 2` mode for GNU-style
#      `--help`-prefixed options.  This is set on the `Options` instance:
#         var numHyphens = 1;            // number of hyphens starting option
#      v3c uses `-` prefix (Plan-9 / classic-UNIX style); some apps use
#      `--` prefix (GNU style).  Compare:
#        getopt_long: short `-x` + long `--xxx` both fixed
#        argparse:    `--long` plus optional `-s` per option (fixed)
#        clap (Rust): `--long` plus optional `-s` per option (fixed)
#        BasicOptions: prefix CONFIGURABLE on the parser — same
#                      Options class supports either single or double
#                      hyphen convention by setting `numHyphens`.
#      v3c's choice of `-target=wasm` (single hyphen, equals-delimited)
#      reflects the Plan-9 / Bell Labs CLI convention from Ben Titzer's
#      systems-programming background.
#
#   5. `-name=value` AND `-name value` BOTH SUPPORTED VIA `consumeNext` —
#      individual options control whether the next argv slot is consumed
#      as their value:
#         var consumeNext: bool;        // if true, consume the next argument
#      Default options accept `-name=value` only; options marked
#      `consumeNext=true` ALSO accept `-name value`.  Compare:
#        getopt_long: short opts take next argv; long opts via `--x=v`
#        argparse:    nargs='?' / nargs=1 / nargs='+' — option-level
#                     specification of how many subsequent argv slots
#                     to consume
#        clap (Rust): `num_args = 1`, `num_args = 1..`
#        BasicOptions: per-option boolean `consumeNext` toggle — UNIQUE
#                      simplification: an option either accepts equals-
#                      delimited only, OR also accepts space-delimited
#                      next-arg, no other variants.
#
#   6. `setUnmatched` CALLBACK FOR ARBITRARY UNKNOWN-OPTION HANDLING —
#      v3c exploits the catch-all callback to implement **cluster-option
#      decoding**.  For example, `-Psmrvb` is a single argv slot that
#      encodes "enable PRINT_SSA + PRINT_MACH + PRINT_RA + PRINT_VST +
#      PRINT_BIN" via a custom dispatcher:
#         def setUnmatchedOption(str: string, val: string) {
#             if (!Strings.startsWith(str, "P")) return;
#             for (i = 1; i < str.length; i++) {
#                 match (str[i]) {
#                     's' => CLOptions.PRINT_SSA.val = VstMatcher.All;
#                     'm' => CLOptions.PRINT_MACH.val = VstMatcher.All;
#                     'd' => CLOptions.PRINT_MACH_DATA.val = true;
#                     'v' => CLOptions.PRINT_VST.val = true;
#                     'r' => CLOptions.PRINT_RA.val = true;
#                     'b' => CLOptions.PRINT_BIN.val = true;
#                     'c' => CLOptions.PRINT_CFG.val = true;
#                     't' => CLOptions.PRINT_STACKIFY.val = true;
#                     'n' => CLOptions.PRINT_INLINING.val = true;
#                 }
#             }
#         }
#      Compare:
#        getopt_long: cluster-short-options `-abc` = `-a -b -c` (built-in)
#        argparse:    no extension hook for unknown options
#        clap (Rust): unknown options error out unless `allow_unknown_*`
#        BasicOptions: `setUnmatched(name, val) -> void` callback fires
#                      for EVERY unknown option, allowing arbitrary
#                      decoding.  v3c uses this for its **letter-cluster
#                      debug-print options** — a Knuth-style TeX-debug-
#                      flag aesthetic.
#
# THE VIRGIL Option.v3 API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   class Opt(name: string) {
#       var consumeNext: bool;
#       def parse(val: string);
#   }
#   class Option<T> extends Opt {
#       def init: T;
#       def parseFun: string -> T;
#       var onSetFun: T -> void;
#       var val: T;
#       def parse(val: string);
#       def onSet(f: T -> void) -> this;
#       def get() -> T { return val; }
#   }
#   class Options {
#       def map = Strings.newMap<Opt>();
#       var names = Vector<string>.new();
#       var vals  = Vector<string>.new();
#       var setUnmatched: (string, string) -> void;
#       var numHyphens = 1;
#       def add<T>(option: Option<T>) -> Option<T>;
#       def parse(args: Array<string>) -> Array<string>;
#       def setOption(name: string, val: string) -> bool;
#   }
#   class BasicOptions extends Options {
#       def newIntOption(name, val) -> Option<int>;
#       def newSizeOption(name, val) -> Option<u32>;       // K/M/G suffix
#       def newAddrOption(name, val) -> Option<u64>;       // hex 0x addrs
#       def newBoolOption(name, val) -> Option<bool>;
#       def newStringOption(name, val) -> Option<string>;
#       def newPathOption(name, val) -> Option<string>;    // alias of str
#       def newMatcherOption(name) -> Option<VstMatcher>;  // Vst pattern
#       def newOption<T>(name, val, parseFun) -> Option<T>;
#   }
#   class OptionGroup(name: string, o: BasicOptions) {
#       def newIntOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<int>;
#       def newBoolOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<bool>;
#       def newStringOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<string>;
#       def newPathOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<string>;
#       def newSizeOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<u32>;
#       def newAddrOption(name, defval, help) -> Option<u64>;
#       def newMatcherOption(name, help) -> Option<VstMatcher>;
#       def newEmptyOption(name, help) -> Option<bool>;
#       def newOption<T>(name, defval, typename, parseFun, help) -> Option<T>;
#       def print(buf: TerminalBuffer);
#   }
#
# Distinguishing features only Virgil's Option.v3 has:
#   - Size parsing with K/M/G suffixes built-in (newSizeOption)
#   - Address parsing with 0x hex notation built-in (newAddrOption)
#   - Vst (Virgil syntax tree) method-matcher option (newMatcherOption)
#   - Per-option onSet callback chaining
#   - Two-tier registration (Options collection + OptionGroup help)
#   - setUnmatched fallback for arbitrary unknown-option decoding
#
# REAL-WORLD Virgil Option.v3 USERS:
#
#   * titzer/virgil:aeneas (THE COMPILER, v3c binary — THIS)
#   * titzer/virgil:apps/Btime — micro-benchmarking framework
#   * titzer/virgil:apps/vctags — ctags-like Virgil tag generator
#   * titzer/virgil:apps/EchoServerClient (TCP + UDP demos)
#   * titzer/wizard-engine — next-generation WebAssembly VM, the main
#     research vehicle for Virgil at CMU
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# V3C'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from aeneas/src/main/CLOptions.v3)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   v3c (-run|-test|-version|-target=<target>) [options] <v3 files> [args...]
#
# ACTION options (mutually exclusive):
#   -help              Print this help text
#   --help             Same as -help
#   -version           Print the version of the compiler and exit
#   -run               Run input .v3 files in the built-in interpreter
#   -debug             Debug input .v3 files with the built-in interpreter
#   -test              Run input .v3 files as parse/semantic/execute tests
#   -target=<target>   Compile to a target platform
#
# Compile targets (from aeneas/.../Aeneas.v3 + bin/dev):
#   wasm               WebAssembly (no GC)
#   wasm-gc            WebAssembly with WasmGC proposal
#   wasm-wasi1         WebAssembly + WASI preview1
#   wasm-wave          WebAssembly + WAVE testing target
#   x86-linux          32-bit x86 Linux ELF
#   x86-darwin         32-bit x86 macOS Mach-O
#   x86-64-linux       64-bit x86 Linux ELF
#   x86-64-darwin      64-bit x86 macOS Mach-O
#   jvm                JVM JAR
#
# OPTIMIZATION options:
#   -opt=<config>      Set optimization configuration string
#   -O0, -O1, -O2, -O3 Set optimization level
#   -maxr=<n>          Max return values in normalization (default 100000)
#   -maxp=<n>          Max parameters in normalization (default 100000)
#   -maxd=<n>          Max scalars for data-type auto-unboxing
#   -maxv=<n>          Max scalars for variant-type auto-unboxing
#   -inline=<patterns> Force inlining of methods matching pattern
#   -licm              Loop-invariant code motion
#   -global-regalloc=<patterns>  Global register allocator
#   -unbox-variants=<spec>       Optimize variants by unboxing
#   -unbox-variant-cases=<spec>  Optimize non-recursive variants
#   -redef-field=<spec>          Redefine program fields
#
# DEBUGGING options (large set; partial list):
#   -print-id, -print-inlining, -print-vst, -print-ra,
#   -print-ssa[=<methods>], -print-licm[=<methods>],
#   -verify-ssa[=<methods>], -trace-norm[=<methods>],
#   -print-opt[=<methods>], -print-ssa-stats[=<methods>],
#   -print-mach[=<methods>], -print-patch, -print-mach-fields,
#   -print-mach-data, -print-stackmap, -print-cfg, -print-bin,
#   -print-size, -print-codegen-time, -print-dead-code,
#   -print-stackify, -print-regalloc, -print-packing,
#   -print-wasm[=<spec>], -print-wasm-gc, -print-wasm-gc-sections=<spec>,
#   -print-wrap, -print-wrap-extra, -fatal, -start-uid=<n>
#
# Cluster-debug option (via setUnmatched):
#   -Psmrvb...         Cluster letters: s=SSA m=MACH d=MACH_DATA v=VST
#                      r=RA b=BIN c=CFG t=STACKIFY n=INLINING
#
# LANGUAGE options:
#   -read-only-arrays, -covariant-arrays, -open-types, -legacy-infer,
#   -fun-exprs, -simple-bodies, -descriptors
#
# RUN/INTERPRETER options:
#   -trace, -trace-parent, -trace-calls=<patterns>,
#   -fatal-calls=<patterns>, -profile=<patterns>,
#   -iprofile=<patterns>, -profile-depth=<n>,
#   -coverage=<patterns>, -icoverage, -debug-extension
#
# TEST options:
#   -test.st           Convert execute tests to stacktrace tests
#   -test.gc=<file>    List tests that allocate, write to file
#   -expect=<path>     Load expected-failures file
#   -ra                Enable reachability analysis before testing
#
# COMPILE options:
#   -multiple          Compile each input as separate program
#   -output=<dir>      Output directory
#   -linking=<model>   Linking model (imports/exports)
#   -program-name=<n>  Explicit name for compilation result
#   -symbols           Output symbols into binary
#   -dwarf             Output DWARF debug info
#   -dwarf-cwd=<dir>   Set DWARF current directory
#   -dwarf-line        Output DWARF line info only
#   -ma, -nr, -wfts, -tr     Various IR / representation flags
#   -set-exec          Auto-chmod +x compiled binaries
#
# JVM TARGET options:
#   -jvm.script             Output Java launcher script
#   -jvm.rt-path=<path>     Set Java runtime path in launcher
#   -jvm.args=<args>        Extra JVM args in launcher
#   -jvm.heap-init-method-size=<size>  Init stub size
#
# WASM TARGET options:
#   -shadow-stack-size=<size>      GC root finding stack
#   -shadow-stack-percent=<n>      Shadow stack as % of heap
#   -wasm.runcmd=<cmd>             WASM run command in launcher
#   -wasm.multi-value              Use Wasm multi-value
#   -wasm.export-mem               Export Wasm memory
#   -wasm.export-table             Export Wasm table
#   -wasm.page-size=<n>            Memory page size
#   -reserved-data-size=<size>     Initial pointer offset
#   -main-export=<name>            Main export name
#   -entry-export=<name>           Entry export name
#   -wasm-sections=<spec>          Restrict WASM sections
#
# WASM GC TARGET options:
#   -wasm-gc-canon-types, -wasm-gc-min-groups, -wasm-gc-one-group,
#   -wasm-gc-sections=<spec>, -wasm-gc-use-ref-test
#
# RUNTIME options:
#   -heap-size=<size>             Program heap size
#   -stack-size=<size>            Stack size
#   -reserved-code-size=<size>    Reserved code region
#   -runtime-code-size=<size>     Dynamic code generation region
#   -vm-start-addr=<addr>         Virtual memory start address
#   -code-start-addr=<addr>       Code segment start
#   -data-start-addr=<addr>       Data segment start
#   -heap-start-addr=<addr>       Heap start
#   -stack-start-addr=<addr>      Stack segment start
#   -stack-alignment=<size>       Stack alignment
#   -rt.sttables                  Stack-trace metadata
#   -rt.gctables                  Stackwalking GC metadata
#   -rt.gc                        Runtime GC support
#   -rt.test-gc                   GC testing mode (every alloc → GC)
#   -rt.fp                        Frame pointer in compiled code
#   -rt.files=<paths>             Files included with every program
#   -ir-alloc                     Generate alloc stub as IR
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ v3c -version
#   $ v3c -run hello.v3
#   $ v3c -target=wasm-gc -output=out main.v3
#   $ v3c -target=x86-64-linux -O2 -symbols main.v3 lib.v3
#   $ v3c -test -ra tests/*.v3
#   $ v3c -Psmrvb main.v3                  # cluster debug-print
#
# Bootstrap note:
#   v3c is itself a Virgil program (aeneas/) compiled by an older v3c.
#   This makes Virgil's CLI library effectively the FIRST CLI library
#   the compiler binary ever calls — it's written in the language it
#   compiles.
#
# =============================================================================

_v3c() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a actions targets opts

    actions=(
        'help' 'version' 'run' 'debug' 'test'
    )

    targets=(
        'wasm:WebAssembly (no GC)'
        'wasm-gc:WebAssembly with WasmGC proposal'
        'wasm-wasi1:WebAssembly + WASI preview1'
        'wasm-wave:WebAssembly + WAVE'
        'x86-linux:32-bit x86 Linux ELF'
        'x86-darwin:32-bit x86 macOS Mach-O'
        'x86-64-linux:64-bit x86 Linux ELF'
        'x86-64-darwin:64-bit x86 macOS Mach-O'
        'jvm:JVM JAR'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '-help[print help text]' \
        '--help[print help text]' \
        '-version[print compiler version and exit]' \
        '-run[run input .v3 files in built-in interpreter]' \
        '-debug[debug input .v3 files with built-in interpreter]' \
        '-test[run input .v3 files as tests]' \
        '-target=[set compile target]:target:->target' \
        '-output=[output directory]:dir:_directories' \
        '-program-name=[explicit name for compilation result]:name:' \
        '-multiple[compile each input as separate program]' \
        '-symbols[output symbols into binary]' \
        '-dwarf[output DWARF debug info]' \
        '-dwarf-cwd=[DWARF current directory]:dir:_directories' \
        '-dwarf-line[output DWARF line info only]' \
        '-set-exec[auto-chmod +x compiled binaries]' \
        '-opt=[optimization configuration]:config:' \
        '-O0[no optimization]' \
        '-O1[opt level 1]' \
        '-O2[opt level 2]' \
        '-O3[opt level 3]' \
        '-maxr=[max return values]:int:' \
        '-maxp=[max parameters]:int:' \
        '-maxd=[max scalars for data unboxing]:int:' \
        '-maxv=[max scalars for variant unboxing]:int:' \
        '-inline=[force inline matching methods]:patterns:' \
        '-licm[loop-invariant code motion]' \
        '-global-regalloc=[global register allocator]:patterns:' \
        '-unbox-variants=[optimize variants by unboxing]:spec:' \
        '-unbox-variant-cases=[optimize non-recursive variants]:spec:' \
        '-redef-field=[redefine program fields]:spec:' \
        '-linking=[linking model]:model:' \
        '-print-id[print internal IR ids]' \
        '-print-inlining[print inlining decisions]' \
        '-print-vst[print Virgil syntax tree]' \
        '-print-ra[print reachability analysis results]' \
        '-print-ssa=[print SSA code]:methods:' \
        '-print-licm=[print LICM info]:methods:' \
        '-verify-ssa=[verify internal SSA]:methods:' \
        '-trace-norm=[trace normalization]:methods:' \
        '-print-opt=[print optimizations]:methods:' \
        '-print-ssa-stats=[print SSA statistics]:methods:' \
        '-print-mach=[print machine code]:methods:' \
        '-print-patch[print machine-code patching]' \
        '-print-mach-fields[print machine-level field offsets]' \
        '-print-mach-data[print machine-level data]' \
        '-print-stackmap[print stackmap info]' \
        '-print-cfg[print control flow graphs]' \
        '-print-bin[print binary code]' \
        '-print-size[print binary code size]' \
        '-print-codegen-time[print codegen time per function]' \
        '-print-dead-code[print dead code/data info]' \
        '-print-stackify[print stackification steps]' \
        '-print-regalloc[print register allocation]' \
        '-print-packing[print unboxing and packing info]' \
        '-print-wasm=[WASM debug/tracing info]:spec:' \
        '-print-wasm-gc[print WASM GC detailed info]' \
